text:
Hey, I have a question about a difference I found between batch updating and batch upserting in the v3 crm contacts api.

When using the Contacts CRM API, I am able to successfully use the `crm/v3/objects/contacts/batch/upsert` endpoint to create or update contacts (I'm using a custom `idProperty` param - email).
However, if I want to just update using the `crm/v3/objects/contacts/batch/update` , I get the following error:
```{"status":"error","message":"Unable to perform update/upsert by non-unique 0-1 property email in portal ID 39874041","correlationId":"562ef628-d647-409d-be5f-5b074f827089","category":"VALIDATION_ERROR"}  ```
Example request:
```curl --request POST \
  --url <https://api.hubapi.com/crm/v3/objects/contacts/batch/update> \
  --header 'authorization: Bearer pat-xxx' \
  --header 'content-type: application/json' \
  --data '{
  "inputs": [
    {
      "idProperty": "email",
      "id": "testmail@mail.com",
      "properties": {
        "some_value": 3
      }
    }
  ]
}'```
Support seems to say that this is an API limitation, but maybe someone else has found a way to make this work? Ofc we can manually parse existing emails, and then only upsert those that already exist, but maybe there's a better solution

I am using a HubSpot api form on a subdomain for my website, and for some reason its not passing through any info other then the form fill info (emails, names) - <https://go.scoopanalytics.com/signup>  How should this form look? (ive been playing with the ip address, but HubSpot wont accept this)

```const axios = require('axios');

async function formv3(firstname, lastname, email, ipAddress) {
    const url = '<https://api.hsforms.com/submissions/v3/integration/submit/23852145/190f191c-ba38-476c-8b7d-834ed34686db>';

    const data = {
        "submittedAt": new Date().getTime(),
        "ipAddress": ipAddress,
        "fields": [
            {
                "objectTypeId": "0-1",
                "name": "email",
                "value": email
            },
            {
                "objectTypeId": "0-1",
                "name": "firstname",
                "value": firstname
            },
            {
                "objectTypeId": "0-1",
                "name": "lastname",
                "value": lastname
            }
        ],
        "legalConsentOptions": { // Include this object when GDPR options are enabled
            "consent": {
                "consentToProcess": true,
                "text": "I agree to allow Example Company to store and process my personal data.",
                "communications": [
                    {
                        "value": true,
                        "subscriptionTypeId": 999,
                        "text": "I agree to receive marketing communications from Example Company."
                    }
                ]
            }
        }
    };

    try {
        const response = await <http://axios.post|axios.post>(url, data, {
            headers: {
                'Content-Type': 'application/json'
            }
        });
        return response.data;
    } catch (error) {
        if (error.response) {
            // The request was made and the server responded with a status code
            // that falls out of the range of 2xx
            console.error('Error response data:', error.response.data);
            console.error('Error response status:', error.response.status);
            console.error('Error response headers:', error.response.headers);
        } else if (error.request) {
            // The request was made but no response was received
            console.error('Error request:', error.request);
        } else {
            // Something happened in setting up the request that triggered an Error
            console.error('Error message:', error.message);
        }
        return null;
    }
}

module.exports = formv3;```
